  "answer": "Chandrayaan-3 is India's third lunar exploration mission and the successor to Chandrayaan-2, designed to demonstrate end-to-end capability in safe soft landing and roving on the lunar surface. The mission configuration includes an indigenous Propulsion Module (PM), Lander Module (LM), and a Rover. It was launched on 14 July 2023 aboard the LVM3-M4 launch vehicle from Satish Dhawan Space Centre (SDSC) SHAR, Sriharikota. On 23 August 2023, the spacecraft successfully achieved a soft landing near the lunar south pole, making India the first country to land in that region and the fourth country overall to achieve a soft lunar landing. Beyond landing and roving, the mission's objectives include conducting in-situ scientific experiments and developing technologies for future interplanetary missions. The Propulsion Module also carries the Spectro-polarimetry of Habitable Planet Earth (SHAPE) payload to perform spectral and polarimetric measurements of Earth from a 100 km lunar orbit.",
